Introduction¶

For my final project for the Data Analyst nanodegree program, I have chosen to use a dataset provided by Udacity during my course work, "pokemon.csv". I chose the subject mostly because of nostalgia, and loving video games. I was hoping that it would also help me stay engaged as well as my readers.

During this project I will load my chosen dataset, gather all the information needed to run various cells answering any questions that will arise.

Thereafter I will be assesing the data and taking note of any information that needs to be cleaned or organized for maximum readability. I will be scrutinizing the given information and gathering any insights I plan on highlighting with my final clean table.

Speaking of clean table, I will go over any noticeable changes that need to be made. Removing any duplicate rows, making the rows and columns uniform and organized. Moving any information to the appropriate column so that data is properly portrayed.

What is the Dataset function?¶

This dataset holds 807 pokemon with 14 columns. I think this is an appropriate amount of information to clean and deduce any interesting facts that can be shown with charts.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

For my analysis, I'll be focusing on which pokemons are the best to battle with. What strengths certain pokemon types have over others . Lets see if the weight of a pokemon has anything to do with their attack.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

There will be a few columns I will be focusing on;

- The pokemon species. There are 807 values.
- The pokemon build and power.
- Pokemon type
- The pokemon stats('hp, attack, defense, speed, special-attack, 
                     special-defense')

def Statbar_plot(value):
    """Display pokestat differenses for Type_1 poketypes"""
    index_group = pk.groupby(['Type_1']).mean()
    index_order = index_group[value].sort_values(ascending=False)
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))
    sb.boxplot(data = pk, x = value, y = "Type_1", order = index_order.index)
    plt.show();
# Loop for PokeStats
for i in Stats:
    Statbar_plot(i)

Above are the histograms that represent the Poketypes and the correlated averages for each pokestat.

This was done to depict the more favorable or least favorable poketype by their averages.

In [496]:
def singletype_stats(variable):
    """Shows Top 10 for each PokeStat"""
    SingleType_10 = pk.sort_values(by=[variable], ascending=False).head(10)
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
    sb.barplot(data = SingleType_10, x = variable, y = "Species")
    plt.title("Top 10 "+variable+" for Single Type Pokemon")
    plt.show()

for i in Stats:
    singletype_stats(i)

The chart above displays the Pokemon who have the most counts in the different Stat variables.

I used a top 10 limit to condense my Pokemon and Shuckle is the only pokemon to be best in more than one stat variable(Special_DEF and DEF)

Conclusions¶

What pokemon would you choose? While going over the pokemon dataset it was interesting to see how the poketypes varied. Out of the 807 pokemon picking the right one can be tricky. If you are interested in a pokemon that has the most attack points choosing a grass type pokemon would better suit you. Need a pokemon that can take a punch? Bug type pokemon have a better stregnth in that department . This is unfortunately a basic statistical hypothesis, we would need more information like the weakness to certain poketypes which would make a big impact on a fight. It's interesting to note that most of the Poketypes in the Top 10 charts also show up in the charts for top 10 pokemon.
